# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ancient-egyptian-royal-ships
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abu-rawash] It is the location of the northernmost pyramid in Egypt (known as Lepsius Number One), the pyramid of Djedefre (also known as Radjedef) and around fifty mastabas (located one and a half kilometres from Djedefre’s pyramid).
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abu-rawash] The excavation report on the pyramid complex was published in 2011.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abu-rawash] Its location adjacent to a major crossroads made it an easy source of stone.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abu-rawash] Quarrying, which began in Roman times, has left little apart from a few courses of stone superimposed upon the natural hillock that formed part of the pyramid's core.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abu-rawash] The sedimentary succession in Abu Rawash area ranges in age from Late Cretaceous to Quaternary but is punctuated by several unconformity surfaces.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abu-rawash] The first burials in the area date to the First Dynasty.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abu-rawash] There is a large Thinite necropolis at the site and a number of objects bearing the names of Hor-Aha and Den were found in the area.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abu-rawash] A set of radiocarbon data for the reign of Den from the site sets his accession to 3011–2921 BC (1σ).
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abu-rawash] There are also a number of burials dating to the fifth and sixth dynasties and a smaller number dating to the Middle Kingdom.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abu-rawash] Most of the mastabas are composed of external walls made up of large blocks layered around a bedrock core with the upper sections filled in with loose masonry.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abu-rawash] On the east side there is a cult niche to the north and a L-shaped chapel to the south.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abu-rawash] Some of the southern chapels have brick annexes to extend them.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abu-rawash] Many of the tombs are anonymous but some bear the names of their owners and some artifacts have been recovered also bearing these names; for example an alabaster offering table dedicated to Hornit.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abusir-papyri] The **Abusir Papyri** are the largest papyrus findings to date from the Old Kingdom in ancient Egypt.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abusir-papyri] The first papyri were discovered in 1893 at Abu Gorab near Abusir in northern Egypt.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abusir-papyri] Their origins are dated to around the 24th century BC during the Fifth dynasty of Egypt, making them, even though often badly fragmented, among some of the oldest surviving papyri to date.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abusir-papyri] Later on, a large number of additional manuscript fragments were discovered in the area.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abusir-papyri] The Abusir papyri are considered the most important finds of administrative documents from the Old Kingdom.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abusir-papyri] They give detailed information about the running of a royal mortuary temple and include duty rosters for priests, inventories of temple equipment, and lists of daily offerings to the two solar temples at Abu Gorab, north of Abusir, as well as letters and permits.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abusir-papyri] The fragments bear the remains of two different writings.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abusir-papyri] The introduction is written in hieroglyphs and begins with a date (dates at that time were expressed in the number of national cattle-counts) referring to the reign of Djedkare Isesi, thus dating the manuscripts near the end of the Fifth Dynasty.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abusir-papyri] The fragmented papyri are written in columns divided into three horizontal registers.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abusir-papyri] The hieratic text on the right summarizes allocations of grain.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abusir-papyri] The Abusir Papyri are a collection of administrative papyri dating to the 5th dynasty.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abusir-papyri] The papyri were found in the temple complexes of Neferirkare Kakai, Neferefre and queen Khentkaus II.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abusir-papyri] The first fragments of the Abusir papyri were discovered in 1893 during illegal excavations at Abusir.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abusir-papyri] They contained manuscripts with regards to Neferirkare Kakai and were subsequently sold to various Egyptologists and museums.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abusir-papyri] German Egyptologist Ludwig Borchardt later identified the find location to near the pyramid temple of the Fifth Dynasty king Neferirkare.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abusir-papyri] This theory was confirmed by Borchardt's discovery of more fragments during excavations at the temple.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abusir-papyri] The papyri from Neferirkare Kakai's complex were found in storerooms located in the southwestern part of the complex.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abusir-papyri] Based on information in the first Abusir Papyri, in the mid-1970s, Czech archeologists under the leadership of Miroslav Verner were able to find the funerary monument of Neferefre with an additional 2,000 separate pieces of papyri.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abusir-papyri] They were mainly located in the storage rooms in the northwest section of the structure.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abusir-papyri] There is evidence that the papyri originally were fastened with leather straps and stored in wooden boxes.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abusir-papyri] Further excavations by the Czech expedition on the site also discovered papyri at the funerary monument of Khentkaus (the mother of Khentkaus II).
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abusir-papyri] In addition to the extensive excavations in the Abusir pyramid field conducted by the Czech Institute of Egyptology of the Charles University since the 1970s, the Institute of Egyptology of Waseda University started excavations at the site in September 1990.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abusir] The pyramid complex is named after the neighbouring village of Abusir, in the markaz (county) of Badrashin, Giza.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abusir] The Abusir pyramid complex is located on the Western Desert plateau at the edge of the cultivated plain, with the Giza Pyramids to its north, and Saqqara to its south, and served as one of the main elite cemeteries for the ancient Egyptian capital city of Memphis.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abusir] Several other villages in northern and southern Egypt are named Abusir or Busiri.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abusir] The locality of Abusir took its turn as the focus of the prestigious western burial rites operating out of the then-capital of Memphis during the Old Kingdom Fifth Dynasty.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abusir] As an elite cemetery, neighbouring Giza had by then "filled up" with the massive pyramids and other monuments of the Fourth Dynasty, leading the Fifth Dynasty pharaohs to seek sites elsewhere for their own funerary monuments.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abusir] Abusir was the origin of the largest find of Old Kingdom papyri to date — the Abusir Papyri.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abusir] In the late nineteenth century, a number of Western museums acquired collections of fragmentary papyri from the administrative (temple) records of one Abusir funerary cult, that of king Neferirkare Kakai.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abusir] This discovery was supplemented in the late twentieth century when excavations by a Czech expedition to the site revealed papyri from two other cult complexes, that of the pharaoh Neferefre (also read Raneferef) and for the king's mother Khentkaus II.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abusir] The Czech Institute of Egyptology of the Faculty of Arts, Charles University in Prague has been conducting excavations at Abusir since 1960, beginning with the mastaba of Ptahshepses, directed by Zbyněk Žába.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abusir] The concession was extended since 1976 with the southern part of the royal necropolis, directed by Miroslav Verner.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abusir] Since 1991, the institute excavates also at the site of Abusir South.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abusir] The excavations are presently directed by Miroslav Bárta.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abusir] There are considerable catacombs near the ancient town of Busiris, as stated in (Pliny xxxvi.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abusir] To the south of Busiris one great cemetery appears to have stretched over the plain.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abusir] The Heptanomite Busiris was in fact a hamlet standing at one extremity of the necropolis of Memphis.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abusir] Earliest tombs on the site are from the Early Dynastic Period, First Dynasty.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abusir] Tombs, including stairway tombs, were uncovered north of pyramid field.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abusir] There are a total of four kings' pyramids at this site, which served as the main royal necropolis during the Fifth Dynasty.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abusir] The quality of construction of the Abusir pyramids is inferior to those of the Fourth Dynasty; perhaps signalling a decrease in royal power or a less vibrant economy.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abusir] They are smaller than their predecessors, and are built of low quality local stone.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abusir] A map and complete list of excavated structures until the year 2019 is available in Bárta et al.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abusir] The map is also published online as a searchable application.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abusir] Directly north of Saqqara is a cemetery of lower-ranking officials of the Early Dynastic Period and Old Kingdom.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abusir] The earliest First Dynasty tombs are on the so-called "Bonnet cemetery" named after Hans Bonnet, who published the site.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abusir] It was excavated in 1910 by Georg Steindorff and Uvo Hölscher.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abusir] Recently, copper artefacts in the collection of Leipzig University, from the site, were studied.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abusir] One vessel, ÄMUL 2162, was made of a peculiar material, arsenical copper with nickel, which could be imported to Egypt.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abusir] Also found at Abusir were substantial remains of a Ramesside temple, perhaps built by Ramses II.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abusir] The temple lies about 500 meters south east of the pyramids, close to the cultivation in the desert.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abusir] The main building of the temple was built of limestone.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abusir] There were three cellars, a small hall with four columns and a courtyard (with mudbrick walls) with ten limestone columns.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abusir] The limestone building was placed within a larger complex made of mud bricks with a pylon and magazines.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abusir] The temple seems to have been dedicated to the solar cult, in particular the gods Ra, Amun, and Nekhbet.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abusir] Fragments of polychrome reliefs and numerous examples of the titles of Ramesses II have been recovered.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abusir] The temple was built above the mud brick tombs of Third and Fifth Dynasty.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abusir] Abusir, Saqqara and Dahshur suffered damage by looters during the 2011 Egyptian protests.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abusir] Part of the false door from the tomb of the priest Rahotep was stolen, and store rooms were broken into.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abusir] The looted structures are mapped out e.g. in this article.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abusir] Köppen-Geiger climate classification system classifies its climate as hot desert (BWh), as the rest of Egypt.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-boats] The **Abydos boats** are the remnants of a group of ancient royal Egyptian ceremonial boats found at an archaeological site in Abydos, Egypt.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-boats] Discovered in 1991, excavation of the Abydos boats began in 2000 at which time fourteen boats were identified.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-boats] They are located alongside the massive mudbrick structure known as Shunet El Zebib, attributed to the 2nd Dynasty Pharaoh Khasekhemwy.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-boats] Shunet El Zebib is one of several such "enclosure wall" constructions at this site dating back to the Early Dynastic Period, and is located nearly one mile from the royal cemetery of Umm El Qa'ab.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-boats] The University of Pennsylvania Museum and Yale University Expedition carried out the excavation of the Abydos boats.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-boats] Lines of mudbrick uncovered by blowing sand were first noticed in 1988 at a site a mile away from the royal tombs in Abydos.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-boats] These brick remains were first thought to be just walls.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-boats] However, it was later determined that they were the boundaries for more than a dozen ship burials from an early dynasty.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-boats] Each ship grave had its own brick boundary walls.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-boats] The outline of each grave was in the shape of a boat, and the surface of each was covered with mud plaster and whitewash.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-boats] Small boulders at the prow or stern of each grave represented anchors.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-boats] Because of the fragility of the boat remains, almost no excavation was done initially as the situation had to be carefully studied for future conservation.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-boats] 10, which was slowly appearing due to apparent soil erosion, was the only boat that was initially investigated.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-boats] For five days, archaeologists carefully examined the midsection of the ship.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-boats] They uncovered wooden planks, disintegrated rope, and reed bundles.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-boats] Wood-eating ants had reduced much of the ship's hull to frass (ant excrement), but the frass had retained the shape of the original hull.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-boats] The midsection of this boat revealed the construction methods used and confirmed the oldest ‘planked’ constructed boat yet discovered.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-boats] The boat's construction revealed it had been constructed from the outside in, as there was no internal frame.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-boats] Averaging 75 ft long and 7–10 ft wide at their greatest width, these boats were only about two feet deep, with narrow prows and sterns.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-boats] Several boats were white-plastered, as were the Abydos tombs, and no.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-boats] Seams between planks were filled with reed bundles, reeds also covered the floor of each Abydos boat.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-boats] Without internal framing, some of these boats became twisted, as was unavoidable without an internal skeleton for support when out of the water.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-boats] The wood of the Abydos boats was local *Tamarix* – tamarisk, salt cedar – not cedar from Lebanon which was used for Khufu’s Solar Barque and favored for shipbuilding in Egypt in later dynasties.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-boats] Lebanon cedar was used for the poles and beams of the Umm el-Qa'ab tombs and had already been imported earlier; pigment residues hinted at bright colors.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-boats] 29A cultural center.” This technology for ship construction persisted in Egypt for more than one thousand years and the standardization of this earliest phase of plank boat construction in Egypt is striking.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-boats] The Abydos boats were found in boat graves with their prows pointed towards the Nile.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-boats] Experts consider them to have been the royal boats intended for the pharaoh in the afterlife.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-boats] Umm el-Qa'ab is a royal necropolis that is about one mile from the Abydos boat graves where early pharaohs were entombed.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-boats] The Abydos boats are the predecessors of the great solar boats of later dynasties upon which the pharaoh joined the sun god Ra and together journeyed down the sacred Nile during the day.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-boats] They would have had many of the important attributes and metaphors that were attached to the solar barques of later dynasties, and indeed perhaps should be called solar boats of an earlier design.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-boats] The Khufu ship, built for the Pharaoh Khufu – Cheops – ca.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-boats] 2500 BC., is usually identified as the earliest solar barque.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-boats] It was buried in a pit at the foot of the Great Pyramid at Giza.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-boats] The Abydos boat graves were adjacent to a massive funerary enclosure for the late Dynasty II (ca.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-boats] 2675 B.C.) Pharaoh Khasekhemwy at Abydos which is eight miles from the Nile.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-boats] Umm el-Qa'ab is a royal necropolis at Abydos where early pharaohs were entombed.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-boats] However, these boat graves were established earlier than late in Dynasty II, perhaps for the afterlife journeys of Hor-Aha, the first king (ca.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-boats] 2920–2770) of the First Dynasty of Egypt, or Pharaoh Djer also of Dynasty I.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-boats] Two more recently located mortuary discoveries have been identified as those of King Aha, who may have been the son of the famous King Narmer, to whom the first unification of Upper and Lower Egypt is often attributed.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-boats] The Abydos boats are not the only find of First Dynasty ships.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-boats] Nineteen boat burials were found at Helwan, but only four of these finds were published.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-boats] Six boat graves were found at Saqqara by Walter Bryan Emery and four of these finds were published.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-boats] Finally two full-sized model boats made out of clay are known from Abu Roash Hill.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-boats] Helwan (a suburb of Cairo on eastern side of Nile) contain a huge cemetery field 20 km south of Cairo adjoining Saqqara in which at least 10,000 tombs have been cataloged.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-boats] The size of Helwan indicates a very large population for Early Dynastic Memphis.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-boats] Almost all the tombs date from Dynasty 0 through the Third Dynasty.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-boats] There are 19 elite tombs where 1st Dynasty funeral boat burials have been discovered that resemble those at Abydos, but little published information is available.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] Considered one of the most important archaeological sites in Egypt, the sacred city of Abydos was the site of many ancient temples, including Umm el-Qa'ab, a royal necropolis where early pharaohs were entombed.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] These tombs began to be seen as extremely significant burials and in later times it became desirable to be buried in the area, leading to the growth of the town's importance as a cult site.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] Today, Abydos is notable for the memorial temple of Seti I, which contains an inscription from the Nineteenth Dynasty known to the modern world as the Abydos King List.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] This is a chronological list showing cartouches of most dynastic pharaohs of Egypt from Menes until Seti I's father, Ramesses I.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] It is also notable for the Abydos graffiti, ancient Phoenician and Aramaic graffiti found on the walls of the Temple of Seti I.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] The Great Temple and most of the ancient town are buried under the modern buildings to the north of the Seti temple.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] Many of the original structures and the artifacts within them are considered irretrievable and lost; many may have been destroyed by the new construction.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] Most of Upper Egypt became unified under rulers from Abydos during the Naqada III period (3200–3000 BCE), at the expense of rival cities such as Nekhen.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] The conflicts leading to the supremacy of Abydos may appear on numerous reliefs of the Naqada II period, such as the Gebel el-Arak Knife, or the frieze of Tomb 100 at Hierakonpolis.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] Tombs and at least one temple of rulers of the Predynastic period have been found at Umm El Qa'ab including that of Narmer, dating to c.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] The temple and town continued to be rebuilt at intervals down to the times of the Thirtieth Dynasty, and the cemetery was in continuous use.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] The pharaohs of the First Dynasty were buried in Abydos, including Narmer, who is regarded as the founder of the First Dynasty, and his successor, Aha.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] It was in this time period that the Abydos boats were constructed.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] Some pharaohs of the Second Dynasty were also buried in Abydos.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] The temple was renewed and enlarged by these pharaohs as well.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] Funerary enclosures, misinterpreted in modern times as great 'forts', were built on the desert behind the town by three kings of the Second Dynasty; the most complete is that of Khasekhemwy, the Shunet El Zebib.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] From the Fifth Dynasty, the deity Khentiamentiu, *foremost of the Westerners*, came to be seen as a manifestation of the dead pharaoh in the underworld.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] Pepi I (Sixth Dynasty) constructed a funerary chapel which evolved over the years into the Great Temple of Osiris, the ruins of which still exist within the town enclosure.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] Abydos became the centre of the worship of the Isis and Osiris cult.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] During the First Intermediate Period, the principal deity of the area, Khentiamentiu, began to be seen as an aspect of Osiris, and the deities gradually merged and came to be regarded as one.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] Khentiamentiu's name became an epithet of Osiris.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] King Mentuhotep II was the first to build a royal chapel.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] In the Twelfth Dynasty a gigantic tomb was cut into the rock by Senusret III.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] Associated with this tomb was a cenotaph, a cult temple and a small town known as "Wah-Sut", that was used by the workers for these structures.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] Next to the cenotaph at least two kings of the Thirteenth Dynasty were buried (in tombs S9 and S10) as well as some rulers of the Second Intermediate Period, such as Senebkay.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] An indigenous line of kings, the Abydos Dynasty, may have ruled the region from Abydos at the time.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] New construction during the Eighteenth Dynasty began with a large chapel of Ahmose I.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] The Pyramid of Ahmose I was also constructed at Abydos—the only pyramid in the area; very little of it remains today.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] Thutmose III built a far larger temple, about 130 ft × 200 ft (40 m × 61 m).
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] He also made a processional way leading past the side of the temple to the cemetery beyond, featuring a great gateway of granite.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] Seti I, during the Nineteenth Dynasty, founded a temple to the south of the town in honor of the ancestral pharaohs of the early dynasties; this was finished by Ramesses II, who also built a lesser temple of his own.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] Merneptah added the Osireion, just to the north of the temple of Seti.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] Ahmose II in the Twenty-sixth Dynasty rebuilt the temple again, and placed in it a large monolith shrine of red granite, finely wrought.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] The foundations of the successive temples were comprised within approximately 18 ft (5.5 m). depth of the ruins discovered in modern times; these needed the closest examination to discriminate the various buildings, and were recorded by more than 4,000 measurements and 1,000 levellings.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] The last building added was a new temple of Nectanebo I, built in the Thirtieth Dynasty.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] From the Ptolemaic times of the Greek occupancy of Egypt, that began three hundred years before the Roman occupancy that followed, the structures began to decay and no later works are known.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] From earliest times, Abydos was a cult centre, first of the local deity, Khentiamentiu, and from the end of the Old Kingdom, the rising cult of Osiris.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] A tradition developed that the Early Dynastic cemetery was the burial place of Osiris and the tomb of Djer was reinterpreted as that of Osiris.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] Decorations in tombs throughout Egypt, such as the one displayed to the right, record pilgrimages to Abydos by wealthy families.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] From the First Dynasty to the Twenty-sixth Dynasty, nine or ten temples were successively built on one site at Abydos.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] The first was an enclosure, about 30 ft × 50 ft (9.1 m × 15.2 m), enclosed by a thin wall of unbaked bricks.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] Incorporating one wall of this first structure, the second temple of about 40 ft (12 m) square was built with walls about 10 ft (3.0 m) thick.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] An outer *temenos* (enclosure) wall surrounded the grounds.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] This outer wall was made wider some time around the Second or Third Dynasty.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] The old temple entirely vanished in the Fourth Dynasty, and a smaller building was erected behind it, enclosing a wide hearth of black ashes.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] Pottery models of offerings are found in these ashes and were probably the substitutes for live sacrifices decreed by Khufu (or Cheops) in his temple reforms.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] At an undetermined date, a great clearance of temple offerings had been made and the modern discovery of a chamber into which they were gathered yielded the fine ivory carvings and the glazed figures and tiles that demonstrate the splendid work of the First Dynasty.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] A vase of Menes with purple hieroglyphs inlaid into a green glaze and tiles with relief figures are the most important pieces found.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] The Khufu Statuette in ivory, found in the stone chamber of the temple, gives the only portrait of this great pharaoh.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] The temple was entirely rebuilt on a larger scale by Pepi I in the Sixth Dynasty.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] He placed a great stone gateway to the *temenos*, an outer wall and gateway, with a colonnade between the gates.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] His temple was about 40 ft × 50 ft (12 m × 15 m) inside, with stone gateways front and back, showing that it was of the processional type.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] In the Eleventh Dynasty Mentuhotep II added a colonnade and altars.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] Soon after, Mentuhotep III entirely rebuilt the temple, laying a stone pavement over the area, about 45 ft (14 m) square.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] Soon thereafter, in the Twelfth Dynasty, Senusret I laid massive foundations of stone over the pavement of his predecessor.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] A great *temenos* was laid out enclosing a much larger area and the new temple itself was about three times the earlier size.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] On 14 February 2021, Egyptian and American archaeologists discovered what could be the oldest brewery in the world dating from around 3100 BCE at the reign of King Narmer.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] Matthew Adams, one of the leaders of the mission, stated that it was used to make beer for royal rituals.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] At the back of the main Oisris temple, outside of the enclosure well, near the cemetery areas, there was the Portal Temple that was built or at least finished by Ramses II.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] Only the front part with four columns of the temple is preserved.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] The temple of Seti I was built on entirely new ground half a mile to the south of the long series of temples just described.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] This surviving building is best known as the Great Temple of Abydos, being nearly complete and an impressive sight.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] A principal purpose of the temple was to serve as a memorial to king Seti I, as well as to show reverence for the early pharaohs, which is incorporated within as part of the "Rite of the Ancestors".
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] The long list of the pharaohs of the principal dynasties—recognized by Seti—are carved on a wall and known as the "Abydos King List" (showing the cartouche name of many dynastic pharaohs of Egypt from the first, Narmer or Menes, until Seti's time).
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] There were significant names deliberately left off of the list.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] So rare, as an almost complete list of pharaoh names, the Table of Abydos, rediscovered by William John Bankes, has been called the "Rosetta Stone" of Egyptian archaeology, analogous to the Rosetta Stone for Egyptian writing, beyond the Narmer Palette.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] There were also seven chapels built for the worship of the pharaoh and principal deities.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] These included three chapels for the "state" deities Ptah, Re-Horakhty, and (centrally positioned) Amun and the challenge for the Abydos triad of Osiris, Isis and Horus.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] The rites recorded in the deity chapels represent the first complete form known of the Daily Ritual, which was performed daily in temples across Egypt throughout the pharaonic period.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] At the back of the temple is an enigmatic structure known as the Osireion, which served as a cenotaph for Seti-Osiris, and is thought to be connected with the worship of Osiris as an "Osiris tomb".
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] It is possible that from those chambers was led out the great Hypogeum for the celebration of the Osiris mysteries, built by Merenptah.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] The temple was originally 550 ft (170 m) long, but the forecourts are scarcely recognizable, and the part still in good condition is about 250 ft (76 m) long and 350 ft (110 m) wide, including the wing at the side.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] Magazines for food and offerings storage were built to either side of the forecourts, as well as a small palace for the king and his retinue, to the southeast of the first forecourt (Ghazouli, The Palace and Magazines Attached to the Temple of Sety I at Abydos and the Facade of This Temple.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] Except for the list of pharaohs and a panegyric on Ramesses II, the subjects are not historical, but religious in nature, dedicated to the transformation of the king after his death.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] The temple reliefs are celebrated for their delicacy and artistic refinement, utilizing both the archaism of earlier dynasties with the vibrancy of late 18th Dynasty reliefs.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] The sculptures had been published mostly in hand copy, not facsimile, by Auguste Mariette in his *Abydos*, I.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] The temple has been partially recorded epigraphically by Amice Calverley and Myrtle Broome in their 4 volume publication of *The Temple of King Sethos I at Abydos* (1933–1958).
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] In The Gallery of Ancestors, also referred to as The Gallery of the List, one can find the Abydos King List.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] This list is depicted in low relief, carved under the reign of Seti I, and it shows Seti and Ramesses making offerings to their royal ancestors.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] These royal ancestors are the past kings of Egypt.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] The Gallery of Ancestors led into the storerooms and the desert behind the temple.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] The Osirion or Osireon, meaning "Menmaatre beneficial to Osiris" sometimes called the Osiris Complex, is an ancient Egyptian temple.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] It is located to the rear of the temple of Seti I.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] It is an integral part of Seti I's funeral complex and is built to resemble an 18th Dynasty Valley of the Kings tomb.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] This was possibly used in ritual purposes with the growing of barely that allowed for the symbolic representation of the resurrection of Osiris.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] Today parts of the Osierion contain water due to the Aswan Dam and rising floodwaters.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] Some of the hieroglyphs carved over an arch on the site have been interpreted in esoteric and "ufological" circles as depicting modern technology, having been the subject of pyramidology.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] The "helicopter" image is the result of carved stone being re-used over time.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] The initial carving was made during the reign of Seti I and translates to "He who repulses the nine [enemies of Egypt]".
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] This carving was later filled in with plaster and re-carved during the reign of Ramesses II with the title "He who protects Egypt and overthrows the foreign countries".
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] Over time, the plaster has eroded away, leaving both inscriptions partially visible and creating a palimpsest-like effect of overlapping hieroglyphs.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] The adjacent temple of Ramesses II was much smaller and simpler in plan, but it had a fine historical series of scenes around the outside that lauded his achievements, of which the lower parts remain.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] The outside of the temple was decorated with scenes of the Battle of Kadesh.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] His list of pharaohs, similar to that of Seti I, formerly stood here; the fragments were removed by the French consul and sold to the British Museum.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] Inside the temple once stood another Gallery of Ancestors.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] This list is also depicted in low relief, carved under the reign of Ramesses II, but is more damaged.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] The surviving fragments were removed by the French consul in 1837 and sold to the British Museum.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] The royal necropolises of the earliest dynasties were placed about a mile into the great desert plain, in a place now known as Umm El Qa'ab "The Mother of Pots" because of the shards remaining from all of the devotional objects left by religious pilgrims.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] The earliest burial is about 10 ft × 20 ft (3.0 m × 6.1 m) inside, a pit lined with brick walls and originally roofed with timber and matting.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] Other tombs also built before Menes are 15 ft × 25 ft (4.6 m × 7.6 m).
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] The probable tomb of Menes is of the latter size.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] Afterwards, the tombs increased in size and complexity.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] The tomb-pit was surrounded by chambers to hold offerings, the sepulchre being a great wooden chamber in the midst of the brick-lined pit.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] Rows of small pits, tombs for the servants of the pharaoh, surrounded the royal chamber, many dozens of such burials being usual.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] Some of the offerings included sacrificed animals, such as the asses found in the tomb of Merneith.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] Evidence of human sacrifice exists in the early tombs, such as the 118 servants in the tomb of Merneith, but this practice was changed later into symbolic offerings.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] By the end of the Second Dynasty the type of tomb constructed changed to a long passage with chambers on either side, the royal burial being in the middle of the length.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] The greatest of these tombs with its dependencies, covered a space of over 3,000 square metres (0.74 acres), however it is possible for this to have been several tombs which abutted one another during construction; the Egyptians had no means of mapping the positioning of the tombs.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] The seals of various officials, of which over 200 varieties have been found, give an insight into the public arrangements.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] A cemetery for private persons was put into use during the First Dynasty, with some pit-tombs in the town.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] It was extensive in the Twelfth and Thirteenth Dynasties and contained many rich tombs.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] A large number of fine tombs were made in the Eighteenth to Twentieth Dynasties, and members of later dynasties continued to bury their dead here until the Roman period.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] Many hundreds of funeral steles were removed by Auguste Mariette's workmen, without any details of the burials being noted.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] Later excavations have been recorded by Edward R.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] Ayrton, Abydos, iii.; MacIver, *El Amrah and Abydos*; and Garstang, *El Arabah*.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] Some of the tomb structures, referred to as "forts" by modern researchers, lay behind the town.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] Known as Shunet ez Zebib, it is about 450 ft × 250 ft (137 m × 76 m) over all, and one still stands 30 ft (9.1 m) high.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] It was built by Khasekhemwy, the last pharaoh of the Second Dynasty.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] Another structure nearly as large adjoined it, and probably is older than that of Khasekhemwy.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] A third "fort" of a squarer form is now occupied by a convent of the Coptic Orthodox Church of Alexandria; its age cannot be ascertained.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] The area now known as Kom El Sultan is a big mudbrick structure, the purpose of which is not clear and thought to have been at the original settlement area, dated to the Early Dynastic Period.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] The structure includes the early temple of Osiris.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] A study on First Dynasty crania from the royal tombs in Abydos generally demonstrated greater affinity with Kerma Kushites, and Upper Nile Valley groups.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] Keita noted the predominant pattern was "Southern" or a "tropical African variant" (though others were also observed), which had affinities with Kerma Kushites.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] Moreover, the analysis too found clear change from earlier craniometric trends, as "lower Egyptian, Maghrebian, and European patterns are observed also, thus making for great diversity".
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] The gene flow and movement of northern officials to the important southern city may explain the findings.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] Archaeologist Bruce Williams has advanced the view that Nubian elites participated with their first dynastic counterparts in the development of the pharaonic civilization.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] Williams also clarified in 1987 that his discovery of the Qutsul incense burner proposed no claim of a Nubian origin or genesis for the pharaonic monarchy but that excavations had shown Nubian linkages and contributions.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] He maintained that detailed, archaeological evidence had found cemeteries of tombs situated in Qustul, Nubia which were described to be vastly wealthier and greater in size than the Abydos tombs of the first dynastic rulers.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] According to American historian and linguist, Christopher Ehret, the ritual practice of retainer sacrifice found in the royal tombs of Abydos originated from the southern region in the Middle Nile.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/abydos-egypt] Ehret also stated that this cultural practice was shared with the Kerma kingdom of the Upper Nubian Nile region.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-i] Amenemhat I was probably the same as the vizier named Amenemhat who led an expedition to Wadi Hammamat under his predecessor Mentuhotep IV, and possibly overthrew him from power.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-i] Scholars differ as to whether Mentuhotep IV was killed by Amenemhat I, but there is no independent evidence to suggest this and there may even have been a period of co-regency between their reigns.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-i] Amenemhat I was not of royal lineage, born to Senusret and Nefert who were possibly related to the nomarchial family of Elephantine.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-i] The composition of some literary works (the *Prophecy of Neferti*, the *Instructions of Amenemhat*) and, in architecture, the reversion to the pyramid-style complexes of the 6th dynasty rulers are often considered to have been attempts at legitimizing his rule.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-i] Texts from the period mention his mother being from the Upper Egyptian nome Ta-Seti.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-i] Many scholars in recent years have argued that Amenemhat I's mother was of Nubian origin.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-i] Amenemhat I moved the capital from Thebes to Itjtawy and was buried in el-Lisht.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-i] Both the *Instructions of Amenemhat* and the *Story of Sinuhe* suggest he was assassinated before he could celebrate his first Sed festival.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] The aggressive military and domestic policies of Senusret III, which re-subjugated Nubia and wrested power from the nomarchs, allowed Amenemhat III to inherit a stable and peaceful Egypt.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] He directed his efforts towards an extensive building program with particular focus on Faiyum.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] Here he dedicated a temple to Sobek, a chapel to Renenutet, erected two colossal statues of himself in Biahmu, and contributed to excavation of Lake Moeris.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] He built for himself two pyramids at Dahshur and Hawara, becoming the first pharaoh since Sneferu in the Fourth Dynasty to build more than one.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] Near to his Hawara pyramid is a pyramid for his daughter Neferuptah.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] To acquire resources for his building program, Amenemhat III exploited the quarries of Egypt and the Sinai for turquoise and copper.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] Other exploited sites includes the schist quarries at Wadi Hammamat, amethyst from Wadi el-Hudi, fine limestone from Tura, alabaster from Hatnub, red granite from Aswan, and diorite from Nubia.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] A large corpus of inscriptions attest to the activities at these sites, particularly at Serabit el-Khadim.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] There is scant evidence of military expeditions during his reign, though a small one is attested at Kumma in his ninth regnal year.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] He also sent a handful of expeditions to Punt.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] Amenemhat III reigned for at least 45 years, though a papyrus fragment from El-Lahun mentioning a 46th year probably dates to his reign as well.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] Toward the end of his reign he instituted a co-regency with Amenemhat IV, as recorded in a rock inscription from Semna in Nubia, which equates regnal year 1 of Amenemhat IV to regnal year 44, 46, or 48 of Amenemhat III.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] Sobekneferu later succeeded Amenemhat IV as the last ruler of the Twelfth Dynasty.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] Amenemhat III was the son of Senusret III, his predecessor on the throne.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] There is no explicit testimony to this filial relationship, however, the inference can be made from their co-regency.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] He had several potential sisters or half sisters: Menet, Mereret, Senetsenbetes, Sithathor, and a partially known Khnemet-.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] Two of Amenemhat III's wives are known, Aat and Khenemetneferhedjet III, who were both buried in his Pyramid at Dahshur.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] Hetepti – the "King's Mother" of Amenemhat IV – might be another wife, but she does not hold the title "King's Wife".
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] He had one confirmed daughter, Neferuptah, who appears to have been groomed as his successor, owing to her name being enclosed in cartouche.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] The Egyptologists Aidan Dodson and Dyan Hilton indicate that Neferuptah was originally buried at Amenemhat III's second pyramid at Hawara but was eventually moved to her own pyramid after an early death.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] The Egyptologist Wolfram Grajetzki contradicts this stating that she was never buried in Hawara, but had possibly outlived her father and was buried elsewhere as a result.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] Two other children, both of whom reigned as king, are also attributed to Amenemhat III: a son, Amenemhat IV and a daughter, Sobekneferu.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] It has also been suggested that Amenemhat IV may instead have been a grandson.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] Evidence of burials of three other princesses – Hathorhotep, Nubhotep, and Sithathor – were found at the Dahshur complex, but it is not clear whether these princesses were Amenemhat III's daughters as the complex was used for royal burials throughout the Thirteenth Dynasty.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] It is assumed that Amenemhat III took the primary role as the regnal dates roll over from year 19 of Senusret III (highest dated attestation) to year 1 of Amenemhat III.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] In Year 20 of Senusret III, his son Amenemhat III was elevated to the status of co-regent, with Amenemhat III celebrating his Year 1 as junior coregent (Horus), while his father became senior coregent (Osiris).
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] The co-regency seems to be established from several indicators, though not all scholars agree and some instead argue for sole reigns for both kings.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] For the following twenty years, Senusret III and Amenemhat III shared the throne, with Amenemhat III taking the active role as king.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] These two kings – Senusret III and Amenemhat III – presided over the golden age of the Middle Kingdom.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] Senusret III had pursued aggressive military action to curb incursions from tribes people from Nubia.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] These campaigns were conducted across several years and were brutal against the native populations, including slaughter of men, enslavement of women and children, and the burning of fields.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] He also sent a military expedition into Syria-Palestine, enemies of Egypt since the reign of Senusret I.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] His internal policies targeted the increasing power of provincial governors, transferring power back to the reigning monarch.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] It is disputed whether he dismantled the nomarchical system.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] Senusret III also formed the basis for the legendary character Sesostris described by Manetho and Herodotus.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] As a consequence of Senusret III's administrative and military policies, Amenemhat III inherited a peaceful and stable Egypt, which reached its cultural and economic zenith under his direction.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] There is very little evidence for military expeditions during Amenemhat III's reign.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] One rock inscription records a small mission in regnal year nine.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] It was found in Nubia, near the fortress of Kumma.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] The short text reports that a military mission was guided by the *mouth of Nekhen* Zamonth who states that he went north with a small troop and that there were no deaths on the return south.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] There is a stela dated to regnal 33 that was discovered at Kerma, south of the Third Cataract, discussing the construction of a wall, though this stela must have originated elsewhere as Kerma was beyond Egypt's control at this time.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] Exploitation of the quarries of Egypt and the Sinai for turquoise and copper peaked during his reign.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] A collection of more than 50 texts were inscribed at Serabit el-Khadim, Wadi Maghara, and Wadi Nasb.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] The efforts here were so extensive that near-permanent settlements formed around them.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] The quarries at Wadi Hammamat (schist), Wadi el-Hudi (amethyst), Tura (limestone), Hatnub (alabaster), Aswan (red granite) and throughout Nubia (diorite) were all also exploited.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] These all translated into an extensive building program, particularly in the development of Faiyum.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] Amenemhat III's activities in the Sinai peninsula are well-attested.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] There were expeditions to Wadi Maghara in regnal years 2, 30, and 41–43, with one further expedition in an indiscernible 20 + x year.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] The temple of Hathor was decorated during the expedition in year 2, which is also the only expedition for which the mining of copper is attested.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] A related inscription found in Ayn Soukhna suggests that the mission originated from Memphis and perhaps crossed the Red Sea to the peninsula by boat.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] A single expedition in Wadi Nasb is attested to his 20th regnal year.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] Between 18 and 20 expeditions to Serabit el-Khadim have been attested to Amenemhat III's reign: in years 2, 4–8, 13, 15, 20, 23, 25, 27, 30, 38, 40, 44, possibly also 18, 29, and 45, alongside a 10 + x and x + 17 years, and there are many inscriptions whose date is indeterminable.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] One inscription dating to year 43 of Amenemhat III's reign comes from Tura and refers to the quarrying of limestone there for a mortuary temple, either that at Dahshur or Hawara.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] A stela retrieved from the massif of Gebel Zeit, 50 km (31 mi) south of Ras Ghareb, on the Red Sea coast shows activity at the Galena mines there.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] The stela bears a partial date suggesting that it was inscribed after regnal year 10.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] Several expeditions to Wadi Hammamat where schist was quarried were recorded.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] These date to regnal years 2, 3, 19, 20 and 33.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] Three inscriptions from year 19 note the workforce of labourers and soldiers employed and the outcome of the efforts resulting in ten 2.6 m (8.5 ft) tall seated statues of the king being made.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] The statues were destined for the Labyrinth at Hawara.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] A few expeditions were sent to Wadi el-Hudi, south-east of Aswan, at the southern border of Egypt, where amethyst was collected.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] These enterprises date to regnal years 1, 11, 20, and 28.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] An expedition was also sent to Wadi Abu Agag, near Aswan, in regnal year 13.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] North-west of Abu Simbel and west of Lake Nasser lie the quarries of Gebel el-Asr in Lower Nubia.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] The site is best known as the source of diorite for six of Khafre's seated statues.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] The locale was also a source of gneiss and chalcedony in the Middle Kingdom.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] The Chalcedony deposits are also known as 'stela ridge' as it was a place where commemorative stelae and votive offerings were left.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] Nine of these commemorative objects date to the reign of Amenemhat III, specifically regnal years 2 and 4.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] A stela was discovered at Mersa on the Red Sea coast, by Rosanna Pirelli in 2005 that detailed an expedition to Punt during the reign of Amenemhat III.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] The expedition was organized by chief steward Senbef.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] Under his direction, two contingents were formed.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] The first was led by an Amenhotep and bound for Punt to acquire incense.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] The second led by a Nebesu was sent to the mines referred to as Bia-Punt to procure exotic metals.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] There were a total of between two and five expeditions organized during Amenemhat III's rule.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] Two of the stelae recovered from the site are dated indicating activity there in his 23rd and 41st regnal years.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] In his regnal Year 30, Amenemhat III celebrated his Sed festival marking the renewal of royal authority.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] Evidence for this jubilee is observedin inscriptions and architectural fragments found at his mortuary complex at Hawara and the temple of Sobek in Shedet..
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] These records highlight the king's extensive focus on the Faiyum region, where his irrigation projects and monumental constructions reached their peak during this phase of his reign.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] At Bubastis (Tell Basta, Nile Delta), there are architectural elements providing evidence for his Heb Sed.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] Excavations revealed a large mudbrick palace complex, covering approximately 16,000 square meters, which is believed to have served as a royal residence or administrative center during the Twelfth Dynasty..
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] A key artifact from this site is a limestone door lintel that depicts the king twice and explicitly mentions his "first sed-festival," providing physical confirmation of the jubilee's celebration in the Delta region.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] Amenemhat III's building program included monuments in Khatana, Tell el-Yahudiyya, and Bubastis.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] At Bubastis, Amenemhat III probably built a palace which hosts relief art containing his name.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] Of note is a relief that depicts Amenemhat III officiating his *sed*-festival.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] Further works include the enlargement of the temples to Hathor at Serabit el-Khadim and Ptah in Memphis, the construction of a temple in Quban, and the reinforcement of fortresses at Semna.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] At Elephantine a fragment of stela bearing a building inscription was found dated to his regnal year 44.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] A very similar inscription from possibly the same year was found at Elkab, which indicates the extension of a defensive wall built by Senusret II.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] Another find at Elephantine was a door lintel of the Eleventh Dynasty, where Amenemhat III added an inscription dated to his regnal year 34.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] Inscriptions with the king's name have also been uncovered at Lisht, Memphis, and Heracleopolis and statues of the king were found in Thebes.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] No site, however, received as much attention as Faiyum, with which Amenemhat III is most closely associated.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] In Faiyum, Amenemhat built a huge temple dedicated to Sobek at Kiman Faras.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] He dedicated a chapel to Renenutet at Medinet Madi.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] This small temple with three chapels is the best preserved of his temple works.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] It was built toward the end of his reign and completed by his successor, Amenemhat IV.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] In Biahmu, he built a massive structure with two colossal 12 m (39 ft) tall seated quartzite statues of himself.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] These face Lake Moeris, for which he is credited with excavating, although how much of this work was conducted by Amenemhat III is unknown.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] The work on Lake Moeris had been inaugurated by Senusret II to link the Faiyum Depression with Bahr Yussef.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] This project reclaimed land downstream at the edges of Lake Moeris allowing it to be farmed.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] A naturally formed valley 16 km (9.9 mi) long and 1.5 km (0.93 mi) wide was converted into a canal to link the depression with Bahr Yussef.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] The canal was cut to a depth of 5 m (16 ft) and given sloped banks at a ratio of 1:10 and an average inclination of 0.01° along its length.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] It is known as *Mer-Wer* or the Great Canal.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] The area continued to be used until 230 BC when the Lahun branch of the Nile silted up.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] Amenemhat III kept close watch on the inundation levels of the Nile, as demonstrated by inscriptions left at Kumma and Semna.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] The Nile level peaked in his regnal year 30 at 5.1 m (17 ft), but was followed by a dramatic decline so that it measured 0.5 m (1.6 ft) by regnal year 40.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] The most enduring of his works are the two pyramids that he built for himself, the first king since Sneferu in the Fourth Dynasty to build more than one.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] The succession following the long reign of Amenemhat III is characterized by a lack of clear male heirs, which many scholars believe contributed to the eventual decline of the Twelfth Dynasty.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] While the principle of primogeniture was the standard, no sons of Amenemhat III are definitively recorded; historical evidence focuses primarily on his daughters, such as Neferuptah and Sobekneferu.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] Neferuptah, whose name was uniquely enclosed in a cartouche, may have been groomed as a successor but predeceased her father.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] This led to a potential crisis in the royal line, with scholars such as Aidan Dodson suggesting that the lack of a clear "King's Son" (Crown Prince) likely caused instability within the royal estate.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] The transition of power was eventually managed through the appointment of Amenemhat IV as a junior coregent in regnal Year 44.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] The exact familial relationship between the two rulers remains a subject of academic debate.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] As Amenemhat IV is not titled as a "King's Son," and his mother, King's Mother Hetepti, is never titled as a "King's Wife" of Amenemhat III, many Egyptologists, including Kim Ryholt, suggest he may have been a son-in-law or a member of a collateral branch of the royal family.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] The brevity of Amenemhat IV’s nine-year reign, combined with his own advanced age at accession, suggests a period of political fragility.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] Scholars often interpret this transition—marked by a coregency necessitated by Amenemhat III's longevity—as a precursor to the fragmentation of central authority that defined the end of the Middle Kingdom.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] His reign ends with a brief co-regency with his successor Amenemhat IV.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] At Semna, a rock inscription equates regnal Year 1 of Amenemhat IV with regnal Year 44 of Amenemhat III (or perhaps 46–48).
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] Several stelae belonging to middle-ranking officials from this period bear the cartouches of both kings, showing that the bureaucracy recognized their joint authority.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] The highest date might be found on a bowl from Elephantine bearing regnal year 46, month 3 of peret.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] This attribution is favoured by the Egyptologist Cornelius von Pilgrim, but rejected by the Egyptologist Wolfram Grajetzki who places it in the early Middle Kingdom.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] The vizier Kheti (*H̱ty*) held office around year 29 of Amenemhat III's reign, as is attested on a papyrus from el-Lahun.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] The papyrus is a business document authored by the vizier in his office discussing payment of two brothers named Ahy-seneb (*Ỉhy-snb*) for their services.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] At that time one brother, Ahy-seneb Ankh-ren (*ꜥnḫ-rn*), was an 'assistant to the treasurer', yet on a later papyrus containing his will, dated to year 44 of Amenemhat III's reign, he had become the 'director of works'.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] This latter papyrus contains two dates: year 44, month II of Shemu, day 13 and year 2, month II of Akhet, day 18.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] The latter date refers to the reign of either Amenemhat IV or Sobekneferu.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] There is one other hieratic text and also a limestone table on which Ahy-seneb Ankh-ren is attested.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] The other brother, Ahy-seneb Wah (*Wꜣḥ*), was a *wab*-priest and 'superintendent of priestly orders of Sepdu, lord of the East'.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] A further vizier datable to the reign was Ameny (*Ỉmny*).
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] Ameny is attested on two rock inscriptions from Aswan.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] The first found by Flinders Petrie on the road between Philae and Aswan, and the second found by Jacques de Morgan on the right bank of the river nile between Bar and Aswan.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] The inscriptions bear the names of his family members, including his wife Sehotepibre Nehy (*Sḥtp-ỉb-rꜥ Nḥy*) who is also attested on a stela in Copenhagen National Museum.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] Khnumhotep (*H̱nmw-ḥtp*) was an official that held office for at least three decades from Senusret II's first regnal year through to Amenemhat III's reign.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] At the beginning of Senusret II's reign, he was a chamberlain, but by the end of his life he held both the office of vizier and chief steward.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] His tomb in Dahshur also attests to many other titles including 'high official', 'royal seal-bearer', 'chief lector-priest', 'master of secrets', as well as 'vizier' and 'overseer of the city'.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] The treasurer Ikhernofret (*Y-ẖr-nfrt*) was still in office in the early years of the king's reign, as is demonstrated by a funerary stela in the Egyptian Museum in Cairo.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] This official is among the best attested for the Middle Kingdom, though there is little known of his family.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] His funerary stela is dated to Amenemhat III's first regnal year and bears his name along with three of his titles: 'sealbearer of the King of Lower Egypt', 'sole friend of the king', and 'treasurer'.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] The treasurer is mentioned on the funerary stela of an Ameny (*Ỉmny*) 'chief of staff of the bureau of the vizier'.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] The latter part of the stela tells of the attendance of Ikhernofret and Sasetet (*Sꜣ-sṯt*) at a feast in Abydos at the instruction of Senusret III after a campaign against Nubia in his regnal year 19.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] Ameny is also mentioned on the 'stela of Sasetet' dating to the first year of Amenemhat III, where he still held the same position.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] Sasetet holds the title 'chief of staff of the bureau of the treasurer' in that stela.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] Another treasurer under Amenemhat III is Senusretankh (*S-n-wsrt-ꜥnḫ*), who is known from his recently uncovered mastaba at Dahshur, near the pyramid of Senusret III.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] The surviving fragments of a red granite offering table recovered from the tomb bear the birth and throne names of Amenemhat III.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] The table further bears numerous other epithets and titles with which the owner connects himself to the king.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] Another chief steward, Senbef (*Snb=f*) is known from an expedition stela found at Mersa and from a papyrus document.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] The stela contains an image of Amenemhat III presenting offerings to the god Min.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] Behind the king stands another official, Nebsu (*Nbsw*) the 'Overseer of the Cabinet of the Head of the South', effectively meaning that he was the head of a workforce.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] Beneath the image are inscriptions recording two expeditions to Punt alongside the names of the expedition leaders.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] The leads of the two expeditions are Nebsu himself and his brother Amenhotep (*Ỉmn-htp*), holding the title of 'scribe in charge of the seal of the treasury'.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] Zamonth (Mouth of Nekhen) is known from rock inscriptions dated to Year 6 and Year 9 of Amenemhat III, reporting a military campaign against Nubia.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] In Year 46 of Amenemhat III, the king died and was buried in his second pyramid at Hawara.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] Amenemhat III was deified and worshipped in the Faiyum for centuries after his passing.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] The Mummy of Amenemhat III has never been recovered, but his advanced age at death is widely accepted based on his regnal length and contemporary portraiture.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] Records from the Turin King List (40+x years) and inscriptions at Serabit el-Khadim (Sinai 53) confirm a reign of at least 45 to 46 years.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] Textualt evidence of an unnamed papyrus and vessel dated Year 46 as mentioned above most likely belongs to him.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] In the absence of evidence for a violent succession or assassination, Egyptologists generally conclude he died of natural causes in coregency with and peaceful transition to Amenemhat IV.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] The appointment of Amenemhat IV as co-regent in regnal Year 44 lasting potentially to Year 46 is interpreted by scholars like William Murnane as a functional transition of power, likely necessitated by the senior king’s longevity and declining health during his final years.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] The construction of the pyramid at Dahshur, the Black Pyramid (Egyptian language: *Sḫm Ỉmn-m-hꜣt* meaning 'Amenemhat is Mighty' or *Nfr Ỉmn-m-hꜣt* meaning 'Amenemhat is Beautiful'/'Perfect One of Amenemhat') began in the first year of Amenemhat III's reign.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] The pyramid core was constructed entirely of mudbrick and stabilized through the building of a stepped core rather than with a stone framework.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] The structure was then encased by 5 m (16 ft; 9.5 cu) thick, fine white Tura limestone blocks held together by wooden dove-tail pegs.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] The pyramid was given a base length of 105 metres (344 ft; 200 cu) that was inclined towards the apex at between 54°30′ to 57°15′50″ reaching a height of 75 m (246 ft; 143 cu) for a total volume of 274,625 m3 (9,698,300 ft3).
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] The apogee of the structure was crowned, seemingly, by a grey granite pyramidion 1.3 m (4.3 ft) high.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] This now resides in the Egyptian Museum in Cairo, catalogued as JE 35133.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] The pyramidion had a band of hieroglyphic text running on all four of its sides.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] That the name of Amun has been erased on the pyramidion can only be the result of Akhenaten's proscription against the god.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] In front of the pyramid, lay a mortuary temple of simple design comprising an offering hall and an open columned courtyard.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] Surrounding the complex were two mudbrick enclosing walls.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] From the mortuary temple an open, mudbrick walled causeway led to the valley temple.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] Beneath the pyramid was built a substructure with an intricate series of passages and chambers, with burial chambers for the king and two queens.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] The two queens, Aat and an unidentified queen, were buried here and their remains were recovered from their chambers.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] Shortly after the completion of the pyramid superstructure, in around Amenemhat III's 15th regnal year, the substructure began to buckle with cracks appearing inside as a result of groundwater seepage.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] Rushed efforts were made to prevent the structure collapsing, which were successful, but just as Sneferu had decided to do with his Bent Pyramid, Amenemhat III chose to build a new one.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] The second pyramid is at Hawara (Egyptian language: Uncertain, possibly *ꜥnḫ Ỉmn-m-hꜣt* 'Amenemhat Lives'), in the Faiyum Oasis.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] This pyramid project was begun around Amenemhat III's 15th regnal year, after problems with the Dahshur pyramid persisted.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] The choice of Hawara suggests that the cultivation of Faiyum was complete and that Amenemhat III was diverting resources to that area.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] The pyramid had a core constructed entirely of mudbrick encased in fine white Tura limestone.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] The pyramid had a base length of between 102 m (335 ft; 195 cu) and 105 m (344 ft; 200 cu) with a shallower inclination of between 48° and 52° up to a peak height 58 m (190 ft; 111 cu) for a total volume of 200,158 m3 (7,068,500 ft3).
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] The shallower inclination angle was a step taken to guard against the threat of a collapse and avoid a repeat of the failure at Dahshur.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] Inside the substructure, builders took further precautions, such as lining chamber pits with limestone.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] The burial chamber was chiselled out of a single quartzite block measuring 7 m (23 ft) by 2.5 m (8.2 ft) by 1.83 m (6.0 ft) and weighing over 100 t (110 short tons).
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] Before the pyramid lay a mortuary temple, that has been identified as "the Labyrinth" which Classical travellers such as Herodotus and Strabo referred to and which was said to have inspired the 'Labyrinth of Minos'.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] The temple was destroyed in antiquity and can only be partially reconstructed.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] According to Strabo's account, the temple contained as many rooms as there were nomes in Egypt, while Herodotus wrote about being led 'from courtyards into rooms, rooms into galleries, galleries into more rooms, thence into more courtyards'.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] A limestone statue of Sobek and another of Hathor were discovered here as were two granite shrines each containing two statues of Amenemhat III.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] A north-south oriented perimeter wall enclosed the entire complex which thus measured 385 m (1,263 ft) by 158 m (518 ft).
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] The causeway has been identified near the south-west corner of the complex, but neither it nor the valley temple have been investigated.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] The pyramid of Neferuptah was built 2 km (1.2 mi) south-east of Amenemhat III's Hawara pyramid.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] It was excavated by Nagib Farag and Zaky Iskander in 1956.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] The superstructure of the pyramid is near completely lost and the substructure was found full of groundwater, but her burial was otherwise undisturbed, including both her sarcophagus and funerary equipment.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] Amenemhat III and Sensuret III are the best attested rulers of the Middle Kingdom by number of statues, with about 80 statues that can be assigned to the former.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] The sculpture of Amenemhat III continued the tradition of Senusret III, though it pursued a more natural and expressive physiognomy, while retaining an idealized image.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] A wide range of stones were used for the sculpture of the king, include white limestone, obsidian, chalcedony and copper alloy.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/amenemhat-iii] Furthermore, the king introduced new and re-interpreted types of sculptures, many of which were inspired by far older works.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] Several **ancient Egyptian solar ships** and boat pits were found in many ancient Egyptian sites.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] The most famous is the Khufu ship, which is now preserved in the Grand Egyptian Museum.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] The full-sized ships or boats were buried near ancient Egyptian pyramids or temples at many sites.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] The history and function of the ships are not precisely known.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] They are most commonly created as a "solar barge", a ritual vessel to carry the resurrected king with the sun god Ra across the heavens.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] This is a common theme in the Pyramid Texts, and these buried boats might be a real-life equivalent of solar barges.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] Similarly, another explanation behind these boats is that they were built for past kings to carry them to the afterlife.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] Because of these ships' association with the sun, they are often found in an east-west orientation in order to follow the path of the sun.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] Many of these boats are found in either a planked form or as a boat-like structure.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] For example, many of the well-known solar ships like the Khufu ship are found as an intact boat or as boat remains.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] However, other evidence of ancient Egyptian boats comes from what are known as "boat pits" or "boat graves", which are pits that are in the shape of a boat.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] These boat pits are often found near pyramids or tombs and are thus assumed to be associated with solar ships.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] Some examples of these include Niuserre's solar ship and the Djedefre solar ship.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] One in Carnegie Museum of Natural History in Pittsburgh, USA and one in the Field Museum of Natural History in Chicago, USA; two in The Sharm El-Sheikh Museum & 2 were lost?
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] A total of seven boat pits have been located within the area surrounding the Great Pyramid.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] Whereas five of them are directly near the Great Pyramid, the other two are near the pyramid of Hetepheres and the pyramid of Ka, respectively.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] The Khufu ship is an intact full-size vessel from ancient Egypt that was sealed into a pit in the Giza pyramid complex at the foot of the Great Pyramid of Giza around 2500 BC.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] It was thus identified as the world's oldest intact ship and has been described as "a masterpiece of woodcraft" that could sail today if put into water.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] The Khufu ship is one of the oldest, largest, and best-preserved vessels from antiquity.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] The ship was one of two rediscovered in 1954 by Kamal el-Mallakh – undisturbed since it was sealed into a pit carved out of the Giza bedrock.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] It was excavated in pieces and took years for the boat to be reassembled, primarily by the Egyptian Department of Antiquities' chief restorer, Ahmed Youssef Moustafa, who learned ancient Egyptian boat-building practices for the project.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] The ship was housed in the Giza Solar Boat Museum, which was created specifically for the ship and was meant to aid its preservation.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] However, the Khufu ship was moved to the Grand Egyptian Museum in August 2021.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] Along with the First Khufu Solar ship, a second one was discovered nearby.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] However, there wasn't much effort to examine it until 1987.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] In 1987, researchers from the Antiquities Authority and the American Geographical Society created a project meant to photograph the inside of the second boat pit without harming its contents.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] They elected to hire Bob Morse, a drilling engineering specialist, to design the drill to prevent harmful elements, like humidity, from entering the boat pit.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] The excavation of the second solar boat of Khufu was started in 1992 as a joint effort between an Egyptian-Japanese team.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] The ship will be reconstructed and displayed in the Grand Egyptian Museum, which was created to house the first solar boat of Khufu and the second solar boat of Khufu.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] Sakuji Yoshimura, a Waseda University professor who is leading the restoration project with Egypt's Antiquities Council, said that scientists discovered that one of the cover stones of the boat pit is inscribed with Khufu's name.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] Associated with and found near the Pyramid of Hetepheres I.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] Associated with and found near the Pyramid of Ka.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] Khafre's pyramid has five pits that once contained funeral boats, with a deep cleft in a rock suggesting the possibility of an unfinished sixth boat.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] There are two boats on the north side of the pyramid and two boats on the south side.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] Both rows of the boats are oriented east-west.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] The western boat of the two boats in the north is covered by white limestone and a cabin.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] These characteristics are shared by the western boat of the two boats in the south.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] These characteristics suggest that these two boats were the Night-boats of Ra, which are the mythological boats that Ra would have embarked on during the nighttime.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] In contrast, the other two boats lacked a cabin, and are thus categorized as Solar-boats of Ra.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] The two solar boats, known as the Northern-Day Boat and the Southern-Day Boat, lack the sharply incurved stern post that is popular in later iterations of solar boats and pictures like the Pyramid Texts and Palermo stone.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] The fifth boat is located south of the pyramid, but is perpendicular to the pyramid instead of parallel.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] The Southern-Night Boat is very well preserved.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] It contains a large cabin and all of the roofing slabs were intact when it was discovered.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] The boat also carried in it part of a limestone sphinx, two plates of redware, and a green basalt roller which was used for moving heavy objects.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] It measures 25 meters long, 3.7 meters wide, and 7.5 meters deep.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] The Southern-Day Boat lies just 11 meters away from the Southern-Night Boat and resembles it very closely, though it lacks a cabin and is smaller.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] The boat carried a lot of fragments of royal statues of diorite and alabaster.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] It measures 22 meters long, 3.9 meters wide, and 6 meters deep.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] The Northern-Night boat is much like the Southern-Night Boat in that it was covered with slabs of limestone, though the cabin that is present is closer to the stern than its Southern counterpart.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] It contained a large drop-shaped bead of blue faience, a redware incense burner, a redware flask, an alabaster model vase, a shell, some blocks of dressed limestone, a fragment of an alabaster plate, a large redware pot, and ox bones.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] The ship measures 27.5 meters long, 3.6 meters wide, and 7 meters deep.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] The Northern-Day Boat is the worst preserved of Khafre's Solar Ships.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] It lacks many details because of this, but it is still reminiscent of the Southern-Day Boat when compared.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] It contained ox bones, a redware incense burner, an alabaster statue upper head piece, a dark green pottery dish, and several fragments of alabaster.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] It measures 23.5 meters long, 5 meters wide, and 5 meters deep.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] This boat is perpendicular to Khafre's Pyramid, unlike the rest of the boats that are parallel to the pyramid.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] It is the largest of the boats and is very corroded.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] It doesn't have a cabin and is thus thought to be a solar ship as opposed to a night ship.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] It measures 37.5 meters long and 7 meters deep.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] Near the southwest wall of the Pyramid of Queen Khentkaus I, Selim Hassan discovered a rock cut solar boat that measures 30 meters long and 4 meters deep.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] This boat was roofed over, and thus is thought to represent a night boat.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] There has been no day boat discovered nearby, though Hassan claims that there may be another boat pit in the area.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] Niuserre's solar temple is present a few hundred meters away from Abusir in an area known as Abu Gorab.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] Next to this solar temple is a brick structure that is built in the shape of a solar boat, discovered by Ludwig Borchardt in 1900-1901.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] Though there is no boat inside, because the building was originally oriented east to west, it is assumed that this is related to a solar barge.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] Borchardt engaged in a reconstruction of this building, as much of the building was in ruin when it was found.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] The building measures 30 meters long, and is about 100 meters away from the solar temple.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] A wooden funerary boat thought to have once belonged to First Dynasty King Den has been discovered at Abu Rawash.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] It is located near an Archaic period cemetery that is in the Abu Rawash complex, which is known for the Pyramid of Djedefre.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] The boat was discovered by a French team working with the French Institute of Oriental Archaeology in Cairo.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] There were eleven planks found that belonged to the boat, each measuring 6 meters long and 1.5 meters wide.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] The planks were sent to the National Museum of Egyptian Civilization.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] Between 1900 and 1902, Emile Chassinat excavated a boat pit that is east of the Pyramid of Djedefre.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] Though there is no boat in the pit to measure, the pit itself measured 35 meters deep.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] During excavation, Chassinat uncovered the Djedefre Head, which is a sculpture of King Djedefre's head made out of Egyptian Quartzite.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] The head has since been transported to the Louvre in the Department of Egyptian Antiquities.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] Neferirkare's Pyramid at Abusir is the largest structure in the region.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] The Abusir Papyri of Neferirkare mentions at least four boats in the area surrounding the pyramid.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] It claims that there are two ships in sealed rooms around the pyramid, and two other boats north and south of the pyramid.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] The Palermo Inscription claims that Neferirkare built a large, brick boat in a Sun-temple built during Neferirkare's reign.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] So far, only one boat has been excavated by Miroslav Verner in the area south of Neferirkare's Pyramid.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] In 1991, in the desert near the temple of Khasekhemwy near Abydos, archaeologists uncovered the remains of fourteen ships dating back to the early first dynasty (2950–2775 BC), possibly associated with Hor-Aha.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] These 75-foot-long (23 m) ships are buried side by side and have wooden hulls, rough stone boulders which were used as anchors, and "sewn" wooden planks.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] Also found within their desert graves were remains of the woven straps that joined the planks, as well as reed bundles that were used to seal seams between planks.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] Abydos had at least a dozen boat graves adjacent to a massive funerary enclosure for the late Dynasty II (ca.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] Their age should be more than 400 years older than King Khufu's ships.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] The length of the structures varied from nearly 20 to 27 m (66 to 89 ft) long, 2.5 meters wide, and about 0.5 meters deep, seating about 30 rowers.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] They had narrowing sterns and prows, and yellow pigment residue suggests that they were painted.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] The length of the structures varied from nearly 20 to 27 m (66 to 89 ft).
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] These are the world's oldest planked hulls.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] The traditions of the hull construction seen in all the excavated vessels continued through the end of the sixth century BC and, with the substitution of nails for mortise-and-tenon joints, into the present.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] An abandoned freighter, stripped of its internal timbers and left on a small branch of the Nile near Mataria (ancient Heliopolis, north of modern Cairo) provides the first instance of pegged mortise-and-tenon joints in an Egyptian hull.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] Not all joints were through-fastened, and the pegs, or treenails, may also have fastened frames to the hull, but for this marks a dramatic departure from previous shipbuilding techniques.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] Found near the boat grave were 30 pottery jars with pointed bottoms, which were usually used to transport beer.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] Excavations conducted in 1894 and 1895 by de Morgan at the funerary complex of Senusret III on the plain of Dahshur revealed five or six small boats.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] He made drawings and measurements of one of the boats (the White boat) from the cache at Dahshur.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] Today, only four of the "Dahshur boats" can be located with certainty.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] Two are in the United States: one in the Carnegie Museum of Natural History in Pittsburgh and one in the Field Museum of Natural History in Chicago.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] The remaining two were on display in the Cairo Museum, but were relocated to the Sharm El-Sheikh Museum in 2020.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] These boats are each about 10 meters long.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] Since their excavation these boats remained relatively inconspicuous until the mid-1980s when a study of the two hulls in the United States was conducted.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] Another boat pit, thought to belong to Senusret III, has also been found south of the Pyramid of Senusret III.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] This boat pit is lined with bricks and measures 18 meters long.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] This boat pit, located south of the Pyramid of Amenemhat III, was made of brick and measured 15 meters long and 5.57 meters wide.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] This boat pit was later used as a tomb, though there is no evidence as to when it was converted.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] The boat pit did not contain any remains for the boat.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] A 'model estate' and funerary boat was found at Saqqara by Walter Emery (in 1957–58; tomb S 3357, 3 ships).
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] At least 3 mud-brick boat graves were associated with First Dynasty rulers and high-ranking officials.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] The Pyramid of Unas in North Saqqara has two boats.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] One the boat pits is 44 meters long and is located 150 meters away from Unas' funeral temple.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] The boats are lined with limestone blocks and are situated east to west, as many solar ships are.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] The two boat pits are next to each other.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] Four or five boat pits have been found at Helwan by Zaki Youssef Saad.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] These pits were around 1st Dynasty elite tombs, and are reminiscent of the boat pits found at North Saqqara, Abu Rawash, and Abydos.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] A 1924 expedition to the Pyramid of Senusret uncovered a large boat pit on the south side of Pyramid 5, which is a pyramid in Senusret's complex.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] However, they assumed that this pit was a tomb, and excavated it as such.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] There are no remains of the boat, and any such remains may have been destroyed in the excavation.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] The boat was enclosed in a brick chamber.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] The western end of the pit had been converted to a tomb, though there is no definitive date as to when this took place.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] It remains unknown who this boat belonged to.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] It has been speculated that, because boat pits are usually built on the south side of their owner's tomb, this boat belonged to whoever owned Pyramid 5.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] East of the boat pit was found a collection of faience figurines.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] Included in these figurines was a cow, 3 women, a dog, a cat, two cucumbers, a bunch of grapes, four figs, four pear-shaped fruits, four grains, and a figurine of a jerboa.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] Though the official Metropolitan Museum register cards list these as being found in the boat pit, the excavator of the project claims otherwise.
[src:ancient-egyptian-royal-ships/ancient-egyptian-royal-ships] A mudbrick boat pit has been found outside Amenemhat I's Pyramid perimeter wall.
